cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.DM. 

The paper deals with a classic problem in computational geometry, specifically computing coordinate-wise maxima of a planar point set. This suggests that cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is a likely sub-category. The paper also introduces a self-improving algorithm that learns salient features of an unknown distribution and becomes optimal for that distribution, which suggests that cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) may also be a relevant sub-category. The algorithm's running time is analyzed in terms of the expected depth of an optimal linear comparison tree, which suggests that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) may also be relevant sub-categories. Finally, the paper introduces new tools to understand linear comparison trees, which suggests that cs.LG (Machine Learning) may also be a relevant sub-category.
